SUMMARIZER="H">

President Bush's nominee for ambassador to Mexico is  28-year Foreign Service veteran 
John D. Negroponte, who as ambassador to Honduras from 1981-1985, helped direct CIA 
aid to Nicaraguan rebels. Negroponte, 49, later concluded secret US aid was a mistake. 
Mexican leftists criticize the appointment but it is expected to be accepted. Rejection 
would be an unusual diplomatic slap. Negroponte was most recently a deputy to Reagan's 
last national security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin Powell; and was an aide to adviser Henry 
Kissinger during the Vietnam war. He has worked on negotiations with Mexico on 
environmental and fishing issues and is known as being good at working the bureaucracy.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
