Today the Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted 13-0 to endorse the nomination of 
Michigan Republican activist Peter F. Secchia as ambassador to Italy. Chairman 
Claiborne Pell abstained, saying the nomination was a mistake. He feared Secchiai' 
penchant for making gross remarks might embarrass the US. Tact and careful speech 
were hallmarks of successful diplomats and Secchia's qualities were opposite those. But  
since Secchia was the president's choice, he wouldn't try to block or delay the 
nomination. Secchia pledged to be more careful in his use of colorful language as a 
diplomat. Secchia is a former Republican national committeeman and lumber industry 
executive.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA072689-0050"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="H">

Democrats said three of Bush's ambassadorial nominees -- Florida real estate developers 
Joseph Zappala and Marvin Sembler to Spain and Australia, respectively; and Seattle real 
estate broker Della Newman to New Zealand -- had no qualifications except political 
connections. Senator Paul Sarbanes led the opposition, saying the appointments were 
prompted by campaign contributions. Zappala's only government experience was 
chairing Republican campaign finance committees. The Senate Foreign Relations 
Committee narrowly approved the nominations Tuesday. Ambassadorial nominations 
approved routinely were Shirley Temple Black to Czechoslovakia, Thomas Melady to the 
Vatican,  Keith Brown to Denmark, and Joseph Gildenhorn to Switzerland. William 
Howard Taft IV was approved as permanent US representative to NATO.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890715-0076"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="H">

The nonpartisan American Academy of Diplomacy rated Joseph Gildenhorn, Bush's 
nominee for US ambassador to Switzerland, unqualified based on a comparison of his 
biography and the job's requirements. Gildenhorn and his family have given $230,000 to 
Republican campaigns. Twenty of Bush's first 29 ambassadorships have gone to large 
GOP contributors. Democrats complain that choice diplomatic posts are better reserved 
for Foreign Service professionals. Gildenhorn, 59, is a lawyer, real estate developer, and 
vice-chairman of the board of directors of the Sovran Bank. Other ambassadorial 
nominees rated as unqualified include Joseph Zappala (Spain), Melvin Semble 
(Australia), and Della Newman (New Zealand). All are in real estate.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
