SUMMARIZER="H">

President Bush is expected to name a female ambassador to Nicaragua in view of  the 
election of president Violeta Chamorro. Front runner is Melissa Wells, 57, currently 
ambassador to Mozambique. Wells was born in Estonia, has no prior experience in Latin 
America, but speaks Spanish. The US and Nicaragua have not had ambassadors in each 
other's capitals since July 1988, when the Sandinista government expelled US diplomats 
on charges of interfering in Nicaragua's internal affairs. Wells' 1986 nomination as 
ambassador to Mozambique was held up for 11 months by Senator Jesse Helms, who 
wanted to pressure the administration into dealing with rightist guerrillas opposed to 
Mozambique's Marxist government.</SUM>  

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900510-0029"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="H">

The Bush administration, eager to have an ambassador in Nicaragua now that Violeta 
Chamorro has taken over after 11 years of Sandinista rule, is expected to name career 
diplomat Harry Shlaudeman to the post. It had planned to send Melissa Wells but feared  
a prolonged confirmation fight because she was a previous target of conservatives. 
Shlaudeman, 64, previously ambassador to Argentina, Peru, Brazil, and Venezuela, is 
expected to win easy Senate confirmation. He agreed to the job only after being 
personally asked by Bush. The Sandinistas expelled eight US diplomats in July 1988 for 
interfering in the country's internal affairs, and the US expelled eight Nicaraguan envoys 
in return.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d119"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ920203-0038"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="H">

President Bush plans to name UN Ambassador Thomas Pickering as US envoy to India. 
The UN role in resolving regional disputes is growing in importance, and the feud 
between India and Pakistan could become the next nuclear standoff. Pickering served in 
the UN during the delicate negotiations that led to the coalition against Iraq, and served 
as a US envoy to El Salvador in the 1980s, during Reagan's opposition to communist-
backed Central American insurgencies. He is sometimes criticized for liking media 
attention. Foreign Service Director Edward Perkins, US ambassador to South Africa in 
1986 when the US imposed economic sanctions to end apartheid, is to succeed Pickering 
at the UN.</SUM> 

